---
import BaseLayout from '@/layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import ProductGrid from '@/components/ProductGrid.astro';
import Breadcrumbs from '@/components/Breadcrumbs.astro';
import SchemaOrg from '@/components/SchemaOrg.astro';
import CategoryNav from '@/components/CategoryNav.astro';
import CategoryGuides from '@/components/CategoryGuides.astro';
import { getCollection } from 'astro:content';
import { buildCanonical } from '@/lib/seo';
import { itemListSchema } from '@/lib/schema';

const categorySlug = 'tools';
const categoryLabel = 'Tools';

const products = await getCollection('products', ({ data }) => !data.draft && data.category === categorySlug);
products.sort((a, b) => b.data.addedDate.getTime() - a.data.addedDate.getTime());

const breadcrumbs = [
  { name: categoryLabel, url: buildCanonical(`/${categorySlug}/`) },
];

const listSchema = itemListSchema(categoryLabel, products.map((p) => ({
  name: p.data.title,
  url: buildCanonical(`/${categorySlug}/${p.slug}/`),
})));
---
<BaseLayout
  title={categoryLabel}
  description="Independent specifications and buying guides for hand tools, power tools, and trade accessories. Find the right tools for any job with detailed product information."
>
  <SchemaOrg schema={listSchema} slot="head" />
  <div class="container">
    <Breadcrumbs items={breadcrumbs} />

    <h1>{categoryLabel}</h1>
    <p style="margin-bottom:2rem;color:var(--color-text-light);">
      Browse our range of {categoryLabel.toLowerCase()} products with full specifications, key features, and independent product information.
    </p>

    <div class="category-content">
      <h2>Choosing the Right Tools for the Job</h2>
      <p>
        Whether you're a seasoned tradesperson or a serious DIYer, the tools you work with directly affect the quality,
        speed, and safety of every job. The UK trade tools market is broad — from hand tools and power tools through to
        specialist measuring equipment and workshop machinery — and selecting the right product requires more than just
        picking a familiar brand off the shelf.
      </p>
      <p>
        At their core, tools fall into a few main families: hand tools (hammers, chisels, screwdrivers, spanners),
        power tools (drills, grinders, jigsaws, planers), cordless tools, measuring and layout equipment, and
        workshop or bench tools such as lathes and bench grinders. Each family has its own performance criteria,
        and the best product for a site carpenter may be completely wrong for an electrician or a tiler.
      </p>

      <h2>Key Buying Considerations</h2>
      <p>
        <strong>Power source:</strong> Cordless tools have largely replaced corded equivalents on site, with 18V and 54V/60V
        platforms dominating from brands like DeWalt, Makita, Milwaukee, and Bosch. If you're already invested in one
        battery ecosystem, extending within it will save you money and reduce the number of chargers you carry.
        For sustained high-load work — such as angle grinding or heavy-duty drilling — a corded tool still often
        delivers better sustained performance.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Build quality and duty cycle:</strong> Look beyond the headline wattage or voltage figure. A tool's
        duty cycle — how long it can run before needing to cool down — matters far more on a full working day.
        Professional-grade tools are built to higher tolerance standards and typically carry longer warranties than
        consumer equivalents, making them cheaper in the long run for daily use.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Ergonomics:</strong> A tool you'll use for hours at a stretch must feel comfortable and well-balanced.
        Weight, grip diameter, and vibration ratings (the HAV figure, measured in m/s²) all affect fatigue and
        long-term health. HAVS (Hand-Arm Vibration Syndrome) is a genuine occupational risk; choosing lower-vibration
        tools and checking manufacturer exposure data is good practice.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Specification depth:</strong> Chuck size, no-load speed, torque settings, blade compatibility, and
        maximum cutting depth are the numbers that determine whether a tool can actually do what you need — not just
        whether it looks the part in the packaging.
      </p>

      <h2>Common Mistakes When Buying Tools</h2>
      <p>
        One of the most frequent mistakes is buying to a price rather than to a specification. A cheaper drill that
        lacks the torque for masonry work, or a saw without the depth of cut for your material thickness, costs more
        in the end through lost time and frustration. Equally, over-specifying for light occasional use means paying
        for weight and complexity you'll never need.
      </p>
      <p>
        Ignoring after-sales support is another pitfall. Tools break; knowing whether spare parts, service centres,
        and warranty claims are accessible in the UK before you buy can save significant hassle later.
      </p>

      <h2>Who Needs Quality Trade Tools?</h2>
      <p>
        Professional tradespeople — builders, joiners, electricians, plumbers, decorators — depend on reliable tools
        as the foundation of their livelihood. But serious DIYers tackling kitchens, extensions, or structural work
        also benefit enormously from professional-grade equipment over consumer alternatives. The difference in
        longevity, accuracy, and safety is substantial, and the products reviewed here reflect that full range.
      </p>
    </div>

    <CategoryGuides categoryLabel={categoryLabel} />

    {products.length > 0 ? (
      <ProductGrid products={products.map((p) => ({
        title: p.data.title,
        slug: p.slug,
        category: p.data.category,
        brand: p.data.brand,
        shortDescription: p.data.shortDescription,
        featuredImage: p.data.featuredImage,
        affiliateUrl: p.data.affiliateUrl,
      }))} />
    ) : (
      <p>No products in this category yet. Check back soon.</p>
    )}
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
